@Sailsman63 You're absolutely right. The fact that automated tests not pick this by default is bad.
I did this mistake due revert the first patch option where i introduced CMAKE_POSITION_INDEPENDENT_CODE instead of -fPIC directly, but due assimp officially support older cmake version than 3.0.2, when this option was included, invalidated the case.
I will fix in subsequent pull request.

@stefanv @rgommers an alternate example: `image = np.ones((2, 2))`. [A pixel is not a little square](http://alvyray.com/Memos/CG/Microsoft/6_pixel.pdf), but rather a point sample at integer coordinates. So @stefanv argues that `cval=0` means that the samples extending the grid e.g. at (-1, 0) and (-1, 1), are taken to be equal to 0, but a sample at (-0.5, 0.5) needs to be interpolated. Using a linear interpolation, that sample's value would be equal to 0.5: the average of 1 at (0, 0), 1 at (0, 1), 0 at (-1, 0) and 0 at (-1, 1).

However, `map_coordinates` returns cval in this case, regardless of the order of the interpolation.

It's unclear to me what the "correct" behaviour should be, but smoothness arguments would favour @stefanv's expectation...

@natoromano

I am concerned about this. Here's my reasons. The TM has a Connections local field coupling the particular Connections instance to a specific instance of a given TM. That TM then has local fields: "columnDimensions" and "cellsPerColumn", further cementing the coupling of the configurations. Furthermore, mappings identifying segments and synapses are keyed in particular indexes of cells and segments, together with reverse mappings of presynaptic cells to their receiving synapses - which all reside in a particular Connections object. The problem is even though we are trending torwards more object representations (with the advent of Segment and Synapse / data objects), columns are still being derived rather than mapped - as cellIndexes / cellsPerColumn which is a local configuration.

Has there been any consideration for how scope will be applied to Connections objects if as you say there will be mappings created which cross apical and lateral/distal boundaries? I.e. Cell 81 will most likely also be redundantly mapped to another body of columns and cells too? Is there a vision for where this is headed architecturally ?  :-)

